# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audit-logging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] An **audit trail** (also called **audit log**) is a security-relevant chronological record, set of records, and/or destination and source of records that provide documentary evidence of the sequence of activities that have affected at any time a specific operation, procedure, event, or device.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Audit records typically result from activities such as financial transactions, scientific research and health care data transactions, or communications by individual people, systems, accounts, or other entities.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The process that creates an audit trail is typically required to always run in a privileged mode, so it can access and supervise all actions from all users; a normal user should not be allowed to stop/change it.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Furthermore, for the same reason, the trail file or database table with a trail should not be accessible to normal users.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Another way of handling this issue is through the use of a role-based security model in the software.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The software can operate with the closed-looped controls, or as a 'closed system', as required by many companies when using audit trail functionality.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In telecommunications, the term means a record of both completed and attempted accesses and service, or data forming a logical path linking a sequence of events, used to trace the transactions that have affected the contents of a record.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In information or communications security, information audit means a chronological record of system activities to enable the reconstruction and examination of the sequence of events and/or changes in an event.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Information put away or transmitted in paired structure that might be depended upon in court.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] An audit trail is a progression of records of computer data about a working framework, an application, or client exercises.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Computer frameworks may have a few audit trails each gave to a specific sort of action.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Related to proper apparatuses and systems, audit trails can help with distinguishing security infringement, execution issues and application issues.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Routine log audits and investigation are valuable for distinguishing security episodes, approach infringement, fake movement, and operational issues soon after they have happened, and for giving information valuable to settling such issues.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Audit logs can likewise be valuable for performing forensic investigation, supporting the associations inside examinations, setting up baselines, and distinguishing operational patterns and long run issues.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In nursing research, it refers to the act of maintaining a running log or journal of decisions relating to a research project, thus making clear the steps taken and changes made to the original protocol.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In accounting, it refers to documentation of detailed transactions supporting summary ledger entries.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] This documentation may be on paper or on electronic records.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In online proofing, it pertains to the version history of a piece of artwork, design, photograph, video, or web design proof in a project.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In clinical research, server based systems such as clinical trial management systems (CTMS) require audit trails.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Anything regulatory or QA/QC related also requires audit trails.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In pharmaceutical manufacturing, it is a Good Manufacturing Practice regulatory requirement software generate audit trails, but not all software have audit trail functionality built-in.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The first 'generic' audit trail generating software came out late 2021.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The software is called Audit Trail Control, capable of fulfilling regulatory requirements for any software used in pharmaceutical manufacturing.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In voting, a voter-verified paper audit trail is a method of providing feedback to voters using a ballotless voting system.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] In employment and human resources contexts, audit trails provide a documented record of investigative steps taken, including complaint intake, witness interviews, and remedial actions taken, specifically in cases involving allegations of misconduct, discrimination or harassment.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), employers are required to conduct a "prompt and adequate investigation" and take "appropriate action based on the findings," making a reviewable audit trail central to demonstrating compliance.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] Multiple regulatory frameworks require organizations to maintain audit trails for compliance purposes.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement hardware, software, and procedural mechanisms that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] These audit controls, specified under the technical safeguards at 45 CFR 164.312(b), must capture information such as user logins, file accesses, and modifications to ePHI.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to review audit logs at least once every 30 days to detect unauthorized access or other security incidents.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires publicly traded companies to maintain adequate internal controls over financial reporting, which in practice necessitates comprehensive audit trails for financial transactions and system access.
[src:audit-logging/audit-trail] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data through logging mechanisms.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] An **information security audit** is an audit of the level of information security in an organization.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It is an independent review and examination of system records, activities, and related documents.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] These audits are intended to improve the level of information security, avoid improper information security designs, and optimize the efficiency of the security safeguards and security processes.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Within the broad scope of auditing information security there are multiple types of audits, multiple objectives for different audits, etc.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Most commonly the controls being audited can be categorized as technical, physical and administrative.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Auditing information security covers topics from auditing the physical security of data centers to auditing the logical security of databases, and highlights key components to look for and different methods for auditing these areas.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] When centered on the Information technology (IT) aspects of information security, it can be seen as a part of an information technology audit.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It is often then referred to as an information technology security audit or a computer security audit.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] However, information security encompasses much more than IT.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The auditor is responsible for assessing the current technological maturity level of a company during the first stage of the audit.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] This stage is used to assess the current status of the company and helps identify the required time, cost and scope of an audit.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The auditor should plan a company's audit based on the information found in the previous step.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Planning an audit helps the auditor obtain sufficient and appropriate evidence for each company's specific circumstances.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It helps predict audit costs at a reasonable level, assign the proper manpower and time line and avoid misunderstandings with clients.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] An auditor should be adequately educated about the company and its critical business activities before conducting a data center review.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The objective of the data center is to align data center activities with the goals of the business while maintaining the security and integrity of critical information and processes.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] In the next step, the auditor outlines the objectives of the audit after that conducting a review of a corporate data center takes place.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Auditors consider multiple factors that relate to data center procedures and activities that potentially identify audit risks in the operating environment and assess the controls in place that mitigate those risks.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] After thorough testing and analysis, the auditor is able to adequately determine if the data center maintains proper controls and is operating efficiently and effectively.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The next step is to collect evidence to satisfy data center audit objectives.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] This involves traveling to the data center location and observing processes within the data center.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] After the audit examination is completed, the audit findings and suggestions for corrective actions can be communicated to responsible stakeholders in a formal meeting.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] This ensures better understanding and support of the audit recommendations.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It also gives the audited organization an opportunity to express its views on the issues raised.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Writing a report after such a meeting and describing where agreements have been reached on all audit issues can greatly enhance audit effectiveness.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Exit conferences also help finalize recommendations that are practical and feasible.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The data center review report should summarize the auditor's findings and be similar in format to a standard review report.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The review report should be dated as of the completion of the auditor's inquiry and procedures.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It should state what the review entailed and explain that a review provides only "limited assurance" to third parties.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Typically, a data center review report consolidates the entirety of the audit.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It also offers recommendations surrounding proper implementation of physical safeguards and advises the client on appropriate roles and responsibilities of its personnel.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The report may optionally include rankings of the security vulnerabilities identified throughout the performance of the audit and the urgency of the tasks necessary to address them.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Rankings like "high", "low", and "medium" can be used to describe the imperativeness of the tasks.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] In certain regulated industries, information security audits may be mandated by law.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The Office for Civil Rights (OCR) within HHS enforces these requirements and has cited the failure to conduct an adequate risk analysis as one of the most common findings in HIPAA enforcement actions.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] To assist organizations in meeting these requirements, the Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC) and OCR developed a free Security Risk Assessment Tool for small and medium-sized healthcare practices.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Information Security Officer (ISO) is a relatively new position, which has emerged in organizations to deal in the aftermath of chaotic growth in information technology and network communication.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The role of the ISO has been very nebulous since the problem that they were created to address was not defined clearly.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The role of an ISO has become one of following the dynamics of the security environment and keeping the risk posture balanced for the organization.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Information systems audits combine the efforts and skill sets from the accounting and technology fields.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Professionals from both fields rely on one another to ensure the security of the information and data.With this collaboration, the security of the information system has proven to increase over time.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] In relation to the information systems audit, the role of the auditor is to examine the company's controls of the security program.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Furthermore, the auditor discloses the operating effectiveness of these controls in an audit report.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The Information Systems Audit and Control Association (ISACA), an Information Technology professional organization, promotes gaining expertise through various certifications.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The benefits of these certifications are applicable to external and internal personnel of the system.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The auditor should ask certain questions to better understand the network and its vulnerabilities.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The auditor should first assess the extent of the network is and how it is structured.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] A network diagram can assist the auditor in this process.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The next question an auditor should ask is what critical information this network must protect.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Things such as enterprise systems, mail servers, web servers, and host applications accessed by customers are typically areas of focus.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It is also important to know who has access and to what parts.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Do customers and vendors have access to systems on the network?
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Can employees access information from home?
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Lastly, the auditor should assess how the network is connected to external networks and how it is protected.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Most networks are at least connected to the internet, which could be a point of vulnerability.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] These are critical questions in protecting networks.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] When you have a function that deals with money either incoming or outgoing it is very important to make sure that duties are segregated to minimize and hopefully prevent fraud.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] One of the key ways to ensure proper segregation of duties (SoD) from a systems perspective is to review individuals' access authorizations.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] For complex systems such as SAP, it is often preferred to use tools developed specifically to assess and analyze SoD conflicts and other types of system activity.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] For other systems or for multiple system formats you should monitor which users may have superuser access to the system giving them unlimited access to all aspects of the system.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Also, developing a matrix for all functions highlighting the points where proper segregation of duties has been breached will help identify potential material weaknesses by cross-checking each employee's available accesses.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] This is as important if not more so in the development function as it is in production.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Ensuring that people who develop the programs are not the ones who are authorized to pull it into production is key to preventing unauthorized programs into the production environment where they can be used to perpetrate fraud.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] In assessing the need for a client to implement encryption policies for their organization, the Auditor should conduct an analysis of the client's risk and data value.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Companies with multiple external users, e-commerce applications, and sensitive customer/employee information should maintain rigid encryption policies aimed at encrypting the correct data at the appropriate stage in the data collection process.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Auditors should continually evaluate their client's encryption policies and procedures.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Companies that are heavily reliant on e-commerce systems and wireless networks are extremely vulnerable to theft and loss of critical information in transmission.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Policies and procedures should be documented and carried out to ensure that all transmitted data is protected.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The auditor should verify that management has controls in place over the data encryption management process.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Access to keys should require dual control, keys should be composed of two separate components and should be maintained on a computer that is not accessible to programmers or outside users.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Furthermore, management should attest that encryption policies ensure data protection at the desired level and verify that the cost of encrypting the data does not exceed the value of the information itself.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] All data that is required to be maintained for an extensive amount of time should be encrypted and transported to a remote location.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Procedures should be in place to guarantee that all encrypted sensitive information arrives at its location and is stored properly.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Finally, the auditor should attain verification from management that the encryption system is strong, not attackable, and compliant with all local and international laws and regulations.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Just as it sounds, a logical security audit follows a format in an organized procedure.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The first step in an audit of any system is to seek to understand its components and its structure.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] When auditing logical security the auditor should investigate what security controls are in place, and how they work.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Network security is achieved by various tools including firewalls and proxy servers, encryption, logical security and access controls, anti-virus software, and auditing systems such as log management.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Firewalls are a very basic part of network security.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] They are often placed between the private local network and the internet.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Firewalls provide a flow-through for traffic in which it can be authenticated, monitored, logged, and reported.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Some different types of firewalls include network layer firewalls, screened subnet firewalls, packet filter firewalls, dynamic packet filtering firewalls, hybrid firewalls, transparent firewalls, and application-level firewalls.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The process of encryption involves converting plain text into a series of unreadable characters known as the ciphertext.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] If the encrypted text is stolen or attained while in transit, the content is unreadable to the viewer.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] This guarantees secure transmission and is extremely useful to companies sending/receiving critical information.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Once encrypted information arrives at its intended recipient, the decryption process is deployed to restore the ciphertext back to plaintext.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Proxy servers hide the true address of the client workstation and can also act as a firewall.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Proxy server firewalls have special software to enforce authentication.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Proxy server firewalls act as a middle man for user requests.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Antivirus software programs such as McAfee and Symantec software locate and dispose of malicious content.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] These virus protection programs run live updates to ensure they have the latest information about known computer viruses.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Logical security includes software safeguards for an organization's systems, including user ID and password access, authentication, access rights and authority levels.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] These measures are to ensure that only authorized users are able to perform actions or access information in a network or a workstation.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Vulnerabilities in an organization's IT systems are often not attributed to technical weaknesses, but rather related to individual behavior of employees within the organization.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] A simple example of this is users leaving their computers unlocked or being vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] As a result, a thorough InfoSec audit will frequently include a penetration test in which auditors attempt to gain access to as much of the system as possible, from both the perspective of a typical employee as well as an outsider.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] A behavioral audit ensures preventative measures are in place such as a phishing webinar, where employees are made aware of what phishing is and how to detect it.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] System and process assurance audits combine elements from IT infrastructure and application/information security audits and use diverse controls in categories such as Completeness, Accuracy, Validity (V) and Restricted access (CAVR).
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] When it comes to programming it is important to ensure proper physical and password protection exists around servers and mainframes for the development and update of key systems.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Having physical access security at one's data center or office such as electronic badges and badge readers, security guards, choke points, and security cameras is vitally important to ensuring the security of applications and data.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Then one needs to have security around changes to the system.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Those usually have to do with proper security access to make the changes and having proper authorization procedures in place for pulling programming changes from development through test and finally into production.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] With processing, it is important that procedures and monitoring of a few different aspects such as the input of falsified or erroneous data, incomplete processing, duplicate transactions and untimely processing are in place.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Making sure that input is randomly reviewed or that all processing has proper approval is a way to ensure this.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It is important to be able to identify incomplete processing and ensure that proper procedures are in place for either completing it or deleting it from the system if it was in error.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] There should also be procedures to identify and correct duplicate entries.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Finally, when it comes to processing that is not being done on a timely basis one should back-track the associated data to see where the delay is coming from and identify whether or not this delay creates any control concerns.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Finally, access, it is important to realize that maintaining network security against unauthorized access is one of the major focuses for companies as threats can come from a few sources.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] First, one has internal unauthorized access.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] It is very important to have system access passwords that must be changed regularly and that there is a way to track access and changes so one is able to identify who made what changes.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The second arena to be concerned with is remote access, people accessing one's system from the outside through the internet.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] Setting up firewalls and password protection to on-line data changes are key to protecting against unauthorized remote access.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] One way to identify weaknesses in access controls is to bring in a hacker to try and crack one's system by either gaining entry to the building and using an internal terminal or hacking in from the outside through remote access.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] An information security audit can be defined by examining the different aspects of information security.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] External and internal professionals within an institution have the responsibility of maintaining and inspecting the adequacy and effectiveness of information security.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] As in any institution, there are various controls to be implemented and maintained.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] To secure the information, an institution is expected to apply security measures to circumvent outside intervention.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] By and large, the two concepts of application security and segregation of duties are both in many ways connected, and they both have the same goal: to protect the integrity of the company's data and to prevent fraud.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] For application security, it has to do with preventing unauthorized access to hardware and software through having proper security measures both physical and electronic in place.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] With segregation of duties, it is primarily a physical review of individuals' access to the systems and processing and ensuring that there are no overlaps that could lead to fraud.
[src:audit-logging/information-security-audit] The type of audit the individual performs determines the specific procedures and tests to be executed throughout the audit process.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] It is a means by which an organization's resources are directed, monitored, and measured.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] It plays an important role in detecting and preventing fraud and protecting the organization's resources, both physical (e.g., machinery and property) and intangible (e.g., reputation or intellectual property such as trademarks).
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] At the organizational level, internal control objectives relate to the reliability of financial reporting, timely feedback on the achievement of operational or strategic goals, and compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal control is a key element of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) of 1977 and the Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002, which required improvements in internal control in United States public corporations.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal controls within business entities are also referred to as **operational controls**.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The main controls in place are sometimes referred to as "key financial controls" (KFCs).
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal controls have existed from ancient times.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In Hellenistic Egypt there was a dual administration, with one set of bureaucrats charged with collecting taxes and another with supervising them.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In the Republic of China, the Supervising Authority (检察院; pinyin: Jiǎnchá Yùan), one of the five branches of government, is an investigatory agency that monitors the other branches of government.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] There are many definitions of internal control, as it affects the various constituencies (stakeholders) of an organization in various ways and at different levels of aggregation.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Control Activities-the policies and procedures that help ensure management directives are carried out.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Monitoring-processes used to assess the quality of internal control performance over time.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The COSO definition relates to the aggregate control system of the organization, which is composed of many individual control procedures.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Discrete control procedures, or *controls* are defined by the SEC as: "...a specific set of policies, procedures, and activities designed to meet an objective.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] A control may exist within a designated function or activity in a process.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] A control’s impact ... may be entity-wide or specific to an account balance, class of transactions or application.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Controls have unique characteristics – for example, they can be: automated or manual; reconciliations; segregation of duties; review and approval authorizations; safeguarding and accountability of assets; preventing or detecting error or fraud.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] More generally, setting objectives, budgets, plans and other expectations establish criteria for control.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Control itself exists to keep performance or a state of affairs within what is expected, allowed or accepted.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Control built within a process is internal in nature.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] It takes place with a combination of interrelated components – such as social environment effecting behavior of employees, information necessary in control, and policies and procedures.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal control structure is a plan determining how internal control consists of these elements.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The concepts of corporate governance also heavily rely on the necessity of internal controls.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal controls help ensure that processes operate as designed and that risk responses (risk treatments) in risk management are carried out (COSO II).
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In addition, there needs to be in place circumstances ensuring that the aforementioned procedures will be performed as intended: right attitudes, integrity and competence, and monitoring by managers.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] According to the COSO Framework, everyone in an organization has responsibility for internal control to some extent.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Virtually all employees produce information used in the internal control system or take other actions needed to affect control.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Also, all personnel should be responsible for communicating upward problems in operations, non-compliance with the code of conduct, or other policy violations or illegal actions.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The Chief Executive Officer (the top manager) of the organization has overall responsibility for designing and implementing effective internal control.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] More than any other individual, the chief executive sets the "tone at the top" that affects integrity and ethics and other factors of a positive control environment.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In a large company, the chief executive fulfills this duty by providing leadership and direction to senior managers and reviewing the way they're controlling the business.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Senior managers, in turn, assign responsibility for establishment of more specific internal control policies and procedures to personnel responsible for the unit's functions.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In a smaller entity, the influence of the chief executive, often an owner-manager, is usually more direct.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In any event, in a cascading responsibility, a manager is effectively a chief executive of his or her sphere of responsibility.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Of particular significance are financial officers and their staffs, whose control activities cut across, as well as up and down, the operating and other units of an enterprise.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Management is accountable to the board of directors, which provides governance, guidance and oversight.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Effective board members are objective, capable and inquisitive.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] They also have a knowledge of the entity's activities and environment, and commit the time necessary to fulfil their board responsibilities.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Management may be in a position to override controls and ignore or stifle communications from subordinates, enabling a dishonest management which intentionally misrepresents results to cover its tracks.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] A strong, active board, particularly when coupled with effective upward communications channels and capable financial, legal and internal audit functions, is often best able to identify and correct such a problem.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The internal auditors and external auditors of the organization also measure the effectiveness of internal control through their efforts.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] They assess whether the controls are properly designed, implemented and working effectively, and make recommendations on how to improve internal control.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] They may also review Information technology controls, which relate to the IT systems of the organization.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Review significant findings or unsatisfactory internal audit reports, or audit problems or difficulties encountered by the external independent auditor.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Monitor the adequacy of the organization's internal controls and ensure that all fraud cases are acted upon.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The audit committee also has a key role in selecting and recommending the appointment of the external auditor, and in approving any non-audit services provided by that auditor, to safeguard auditor independence.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] They also ensure that benefit-related performance measures are properly used by the management of the organization.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] All staff members should be responsible for reporting problems of operations, monitoring and improving their performance, and monitoring non-compliance with the corporate policies and various professional codes, or violations of policies, standards, practices and procedures.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Their particular responsibilities should be documented in their individual personnel files.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In performance management activities they take part in all compliance and performance data collection and processing activities as they are part of various organizational units and may also be responsible for various compliance and operational-related activities of the organization.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Staff and junior managers may be involved in evaluating the controls within their own organizational unit using a control self-assessment.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Advances in technology and data analysis have led to the development of numerous tools which can automatically evaluate the effectiveness of internal controls.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Used in conjunction with continuous auditing, continuous controls monitoring provides assurance on financial information flowing through the business processes.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] There are laws and regulations on internal control related to financial reporting in a number of jurisdictions.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] In the U.S. these regulations are specifically established by Sections 404 and 302 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal control can provide reasonable, not absolute, assurance that the objectives of an organization will be met.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The concept of reasonable assurance implies a high degree of assurance, constrained by the costs and benefits of establishing incremental control procedures.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Effective internal control implies the organization generates reliable financial reporting and substantially complies with the laws and regulations that apply to it.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] However, whether an organization achieves operational and strategic objectives may depend on factors outside the enterprise, such as competition or technological innovation.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] These factors are outside the scope of internal control; therefore, effective internal control provides only timely information or feedback on progress towards the achievement of operational and strategic objectives, but cannot guarantee their achievement.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] b) the nature of the control activity itself.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Assertions are representations by the management embodied in the financial statements.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Further such fixed assets must be disclosed and represented correctly in the financial statement according to the financial reporting framework applicable to the company.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Controls may be defined against the particular financial statement assertion to which they relate.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Existence/Occurrence/Validity: Only valid or authorized transactions are processed.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Rights and obligations: Assets are the rights of the organization and the liabilities are its obligations as of a given date.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Completeness: All transactions are processed that should be.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Valuation: Transactions are valued accurately using the proper methodology, such as a specified means of computation or formula.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Control activities may also be explained by the type or nature of activity.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Control precision describes the alignment or correlation between a particular control procedure and a given control objective or risk.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] A control with direct impact on the achievement of an objective (or mitigation of a risk) is said to be more precise than one with indirect impact on the objective or risk.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Precision is distinct from sufficiency; that is, multiple controls with varying degrees of precision may be involved in achieving a control objective or mitigating a risk.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Precision is an important factor in performing a SOX 404 top-down risk assessment.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] After identifying specific financial reporting material misstatement risks, management and the external auditors are required to identify and test controls that mitigate the risks.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] This involves making judgments regarding both precision and sufficiency of controls required to mitigate the risks.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Risks and controls may be entity-level or assertion-level under the PCAOB guidance.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Entity-level controls are identified to address entity-level risks.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] However, a combination of entity-level and assertion-level controls are typically identified to address assertion-level risks.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The PCAOB set forth a three-level hierarchy for considering the precision of entity-level controls.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Later guidance by the PCAOB regarding small public firms provided several factors to consider in assessing precision.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal control plays an important role in the prevention and detection of fraud.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Under the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, companies are required to perform a fraud risk assessment and assess related controls.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] This typically involves identifying scenarios in which theft or loss could occur and determining if existing control procedures effectively manage the risk to an acceptable level.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The risk that senior management might override important financial controls to manipulate financial reporting is also a key area of focus in fraud risk assessment.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] The AICPA, IIA, and ACFE also sponsored a guide published during 2008 that includes a framework for helping organizations manage their fraud risk.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Controls can be evaluated and improved to make a business operation run more effectively and efficiently.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] For example, automating controls that are manual in nature can save costs and improve transaction processing.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] If the internal control system is thought of by executives as only a means of preventing fraud and complying with laws and regulations, an important opportunity may be missed.
[src:audit-logging/internal-control] Internal controls can also be used to systematically improve businesses, particularly in regard to effectiveness and efficiency.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:audit-logging/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet is focused on providing developers with concentrated guidance on building application logging mechanisms, especially related to security logging.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Many systems enable network device, operating system, web server, mail server and database server logging, but often custom application event logging is missing, disabled or poorly configured.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It provides much greater insight than infrastructure logging alone.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Web application (e.g. web site or web service) logging is much more than having web server logs enabled (e.g. using Extended Log File Format).
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should be consistent within the application, consistent across an organization's application portfolio and use industry standards where relevant, so the logged event data can be consumed, correlated, analyzed and managed by a wide variety of systems.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should always be included for security events.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logs are invaluable data for both security and operational use cases.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Process monitoring, audit, and transaction logs/trails etc. are usually collected for different purposes than security event logging, and this often means they should be kept separate.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The types of events and details collected will tend to be different.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For example a PCIDSS audit log will contain a chronological record of activities to provide an independently verifiable trail that permits reconstruction, review and examination to determine the original sequence of attributable transactions.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It is important not to log too much, or too little.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Use knowledge of the intended purposes to guide what, when and how much.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The remainder of this cheat sheet primarily discusses security event logging.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The application itself has access to a wide range of information events that should be used to generate log entries.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Thus, the primary event data source is the application code itself.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The application has the most information about the user (e.g. identity, roles, permissions) and the context of the event (target, action, outcomes), and often this data is not available to either infrastructure devices, or even closely-related applications.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The degree of confidence in the event information has to be considered when including event data from systems in a different trust zone.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Data may be missing, modified, forged, replayed and could be malicious – it must always be treated as untrusted data.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider how the source can be verified, and how integrity and non-repudiation can be enforced.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications commonly write event log data to the file system or a database (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications installed on desktops and on mobile devices may use local storage and local databases, as well as sending data to remote storage.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Your selected framework may limit the available choices.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] All types of applications may send event data to remote systems (instead of or as well as more local storage).
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This could be a centralized log collection and management system (e.g.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] SIEM or SEM) or another application elsewhere.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether the application can simply send its event stream, unbuffered, to stdout, for management by the execution environment.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider separate files/tables for extended event information such as error stack traces or a record of HTTP request and response headers and bodies.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The level and content of security monitoring, alerting, and reporting needs to be set during the requirements and design stage of projects, and should be proportionate to the information security risks.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This can then be used to define what should be logged.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] There is no one size fits all solution, and a blind checklist approach can lead to unnecessary "alarm fog" that means real problems go undetected.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Each log entry needs to include sufficient information for the intended subsequent monitoring and analysis.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It could be full content data, but is more likely to be an extract or just summary properties.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The application logs must record "when, where, who and what" for each event.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For more information on these, see the "other" related articles listed at the end, especially the comprehensive article by Anton Chuvakin and Gunnar Peterson.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Never log data unless it is legally sanctioned.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, intercepting some communications, monitoring employees, and collecting some data without consent may all be illegal.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Never exclude any events from "known" users such as other internal systems, "trusted" third parties, search engine robots, uptime/process and other remote monitoring systems, pen testers, auditors.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] However, you may want to include a classification flag for each of these in the recorded data.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider using personal data de-identification techniques such as deletion, scrambling or pseudonymization of direct and indirect identifiers where the individual's identity is not required, or the risk is considered too great.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In some systems, sanitization can be undertaken post log collection, and prior to log display.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] It may be desirable to be able to alter the level of logging (type of events based on severity or threat level, amount of detail recorded).
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] If your development framework supports suitable logging mechanisms, use or build upon that.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, implement an application-wide log handler which can be called from other modules/components.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Document the interface referencing the organisation-specific event classification and description syntax requirements.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] If possible create this log handler as a standard module that can be thoroughly tested, deployed in multiple applications, and added to a list of approved and recommended modules.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Where possible, record data in a standard format, or at least ensure it can be exported/broadcast using an industry-standard format.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In some cases, events may be relayed or collected together in intermediate points.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In the latter some data may be aggregated or summarized before forwarding on to a central repository and analysis system.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] As an example, the diagram below shows a service that provides business functionality to customers.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] We recommend creating a centralized system for collecting logs.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] There may be many such services, but all of them must securely collect logs in a centralized system.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, all external requests from users go through the API management service, see application in MIDDLEWARE 2 segment.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] As you can see in the image above, at the network level, the processes of saving and downloading logs require opening different network accesses (ports), arrows are highlighted in different colors.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Also, saving and downloading are performed by different applications.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Enable processes to detect whether logging has stopped, and to identify tampering or unauthorized access and deletion (see protection below).
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] The logging mechanisms and collected event data must be protected from mis-use such as tampering in transit, and unauthorized access, modification and deletion once stored.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Logs may contain personal and other sensitive information, or the data may contain information regarding the application's code and logic.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] In addition, the collected information in the logs may itself have business value (to competitors, gossip-mongers, journalists and activists) such as allowing the estimate of revenues, or providing performance information about employees.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] This data may be held on end devices, at intermediate points, in centralized repositories and in archives and backups.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether parts of the data may need to be excluded, masked, sanitized, hashed, or encrypted during examination or extraction.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] See `NIST SP 800-92` Guide to Computer Security Log Management for more guidance.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Log data, temporary debug logs, and backups/copies/extractions, must not be destroyed before the duration of the required data retention period, and must not be kept beyond this time.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Legal, regulatory and contractual obligations may impact on these periods.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Because of their usefulness as a defense, logs may be a target of attacks.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] See also OWASP Log Injection and CWE-117.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] A confidentiality attack enables an unauthorized party to access sensitive information stored in logs.
[src:audit-logging/logging-cheat-sheet] Which information should be modifiable by whom?
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] In law, **non-repudiation** is a situation where a statement's author cannot successfully dispute its authorship or the validity of an associated contract.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] The term is often seen in a legal setting when the authenticity of a signature is being challenged.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] In such an instance, the authenticity is being "repudiated".
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] For example, Mallory buys a cell phone for $100, writes a paper cheque as payment, and signs the cheque with a pen.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Later, she finds that she can't afford it, and claims that the cheque is a forgery.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] The signature guarantees that only Mallory could have signed the cheque, and so Mallory's bank must pay the cheque.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] This is non-repudiation; Mallory cannot repudiate the cheque.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] In practice, pen-and-paper signatures are not hard to forge, but digital signatures can be very hard to break.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] In general, *non-repudiation* involves associating actions or changes with a unique individual.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] For example, a secure area may use a key card access system where non-repudiation would be violated if key cards were shared or if lost and stolen cards were not immediately reported.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Similarly, the owner of a computer account must not allow others to use it, such as by giving away their password, and a policy should be implemented to enforce this.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Proof of data integrity is typically the easiest of these requirements to accomplish.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] A data hash such as SHA2 usually ensures that the data will not be changed undetectably.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Even with this safeguard, it is possible to tamper with data in transit, either through a man-in-the-middle attack or phishing.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Because of this, data integrity is best assessed when the recipient already possesses the necessary verification information, such as after being mutually authenticated.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] The common method to provide non-repudiation in the context of digital communications or storage is Digital Signatures, a more powerful tool that provides non-repudiation in a *publicly verifiable* manner.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Message Authentication Codes (MAC), useful when the communicating parties have arranged to use a shared secret that they both possess, does not give non-repudiation.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] A misconception is that encrypting, per se, provides authentication "If the message decrypts properly then it is authentic", which is not the case.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] MAC can be subject to several types of attacks, like: message reordering, block substitution, block repetition, ....
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Thus just providing message integrity and authentication, but not non-repudiation.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] To achieve non-repudiation one must trust a service (a certificate generated by a trusted third party (TTP) called certificate authority (CA)) which prevents an entity from denying previous commitments or actions (e.g. sending message A to B).
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] The difference between MAC and Digital Signatures, one uses symmetric keys and the other asymmetric keys (provided by the CA).
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Note that the goal is not to achieve confidentiality: in both cases (MAC or digital signature), one simply appends a tag to the otherwise plaintext, visible message.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] If confidentiality is also required, then an encryption scheme can be combined with the digital signature, or some form of authenticated encryption could be used.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Verifying the digital origin means that the certified/signed data likely came from someone who possesses the private key corresponding to the signing certificate.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] If the key used to digitally sign a message is not properly safeguarded by the original owner, digital forgery can occur.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] To mitigate the risk of people repudiating their own signatures, the standard approach is to involve a trusted third party.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] The two most common TTPs are forensic analysts and notaries.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] A forensic analyst specializing in handwriting can compare some signature to a known valid signature and assess its legitimacy.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] A notary is a witness who verifies an individual's identity by checking other credentials and affixing their certification that the person signing is who they claim to be.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] A notary provides the extra benefit of maintaining independent logs of their transactions, complete with the types of credentials checked, and another signature that can be verified by the forensic analyst.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] For digital information, the most commonly employed TTP is a certificate authority, which issues public key certificates.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] A public key certificate can be used by anyone to verify digital signatures without a shared secret between the signer and the verifier.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] The role of the certificate authority is to authoritatively state to whom the certificate belongs, meaning that this person or entity possesses the corresponding private key.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] However, a digital signature is forensically identical in both legitimate and forged uses.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Someone who possesses the private key can create a valid digital signature.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] Protecting the private key is the idea behind some smart cards such as the United States Department of Defense's Common Access Card (CAC), which never lets the key leave the card.
[src:audit-logging/nonrepudiation] That means that to use the card for encryption and digital signatures, a person needs the personal identification number (PIN) code necessary to unlock it.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:audit-logging/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
